The main approaches that were proposed in management in the 21st century are presented on this table,

26:59.000 --> 27:02.000
which you can see on the slide.

27:02.000 --> 27:07.000
And, accordingly, we will focus on these approaches.

27:07.000 --> 27:17.000
As for management thinking, it covers the period from the end of the 19th century to the end of the 20th century,

27:17.000 --> 27:19.000
to the beginning of the 21st century.

27:19.000 --> 27:28.000
And we can see that each of the proposed approaches takes a certain period of time.

27:28.000 --> 27:34.000
Please note that these periods of time are decades, not a year or two months.

27:34.000 --> 27:39.000
These are decades, sometimes even half a century,

27:39.000 --> 27:48.000
during which certain or other positions are tested, which are typical of each approach.

27:48.000 --> 27:57.000
Let's now go through this table and see how these approaches are interconnected,

27:57.000 --> 28:04.000
how each of these approaches is a certain starting point for the next approach.

28:04.000 --> 28:06.000
Why do these approaches arise one after another?

28:06.000 --> 28:13.000
They are mostly in a sequence, because first there is a certain approach.

28:13.000 --> 28:19.000
It has some positive results, and it begins to be implemented, it begins to be used.

28:19.000 --> 28:25.000
But as it is implemented, as it is used, its limitations are revealed.

28:25.000 --> 28:30.000
On the one hand, new socio-economic conditions arise.

28:30.000 --> 28:33.000
Remember the definition of management that we gave.

28:33.000 --> 28:36.000
Different socio-technical conditions arise.

28:36.000 --> 28:39.000
Again, let's remember, we give the definition of management.

28:39.000 --> 28:48.000
Systemic relations that exist between people, that exist between manufacturers, change.

28:49.000 --> 28:57.000
And, accordingly, the need for the final result that we want to achieve changes.

28:57.000 --> 29:08.000
Accordingly, those or other achievements that were achieved in management should be modified, modernized, and adapted.

29:08.000 --> 29:14.000
No matter how good they are, management is a fundamentally dynamic system.

29:15.000 --> 29:26.000
If management becomes static, it is doomed, because all processes are constantly changing.

29:26.000 --> 29:30.000
And there is no need to look for these decisions once and for all.

29:30.000 --> 29:34.000
Unfortunately, they do not exist.

29:34.000 --> 29:44.000
Or, let's be more careful, in any case, there are still no unambiguous, just approaches in all times and for all circumstances.

29:44.000 --> 29:49.000
Well, maybe they will not be found further, then we will consider and study them.

29:49.000 --> 29:55.000
So, let's now consider these approaches that are presented here.

29:56.000 --> 30:05.000
The emergence of management as a scientific discipline is connected with the name of Frederick Winslow Taylor.

30:05.000 --> 30:17.000
And as for Taylor, he was actually the founder of management as a kind of professional activity.

30:17.000 --> 30:26.000
Again, remember when we talked about, gave a definition of management, we emphasized that management is primarily a professional activity.

30:26.000 --> 30:38.000
So, the first person who paid attention to this, the first person who made management a profession, was Taylor.

30:39.000 --> 30:44.000
Taylor lived in the 19th century, the main part of his life took place in the 19th century.

30:44.000 --> 30:47.000
He was born in 1856, died in 1915.

30:47.000 --> 31:01.000
And this time was characterized by the development of industry, the emergence and establishment of capitalist economic relations.

31:02.000 --> 31:13.000
And therefore, the task arose, the need arose to analyze, to structure those new economic relations that arise.

31:13.000 --> 31:16.000
To a significant extent, this was done by economists.

31:16.000 --> 31:21.000
But as for Taylor, he was again a practitioner.

31:21.000 --> 31:33.000
And it was Taylor who drew attention to the fact that to a significant extent, if we want to get a specific result in production, in service,

31:33.000 --> 31:38.000
then in a certain way it is necessary to organize the working conditions.

31:38.000 --> 31:42.000
There are different factories, and Taylor, of course, saw it all.

31:42.000 --> 31:50.000
These factories can have the same equipment, the same number of people can work at these factories.

31:50.000 --> 31:54.000
But the result at the output of each of these factories is different.

31:54.000 --> 31:55.000
Why?

31:55.000 --> 31:57.000
The machines are the same.

31:57.000 --> 32:04.000
Well, people are different, of course, but on the other hand, these are people who work on machines.

32:04.000 --> 32:11.000
The number of factory indicators is the same, the result is different.

32:11.000 --> 32:12.000
Why?

32:12.000 --> 32:18.000
It is quite possible that this situation is due to the fact that it is necessary to look for a problem in people.

32:18.000 --> 32:21.000
The machines are the same, people are different.

32:21.000 --> 32:32.000
But as for Taylor, he did not consider the problem of motivation of specific people.

32:32.000 --> 32:42.000
He drew attention to the fact that a lot, from the point of view of business, from the point of view of the final result,

32:42.000 --> 32:47.000
determines how management is organized by these people.

32:47.000 --> 32:56.000
How well they know what to do, when to do it, under what conditions to do it, in what order to do it,

32:56.000 --> 33:03.000
depending on how their working day is organized, how many breaks they have, when they have a lunch break,

33:03.000 --> 33:09.000
how the interaction between these people is organized, how the management of these people is organized.

33:10.000 --> 33:25.000
Based on his observations, Taylor realized that the final economic results that will be obtained depend on the administration.

33:25.000 --> 33:33.000
It is the administration, because the administration in the 19th century was engaged in management.

33:33.000 --> 33:40.000
It was the administration in the 19th century, the administration of factories, that decided the main functions that stood before it.

33:40.000 --> 33:45.000
The function of planning, the function of organization, the function of motivation and the function of control.

33:45.000 --> 33:52.000
Depending on how this or that function is implemented, how the corresponding tasks are solved,

33:52.000 --> 33:56.000
which are in front of the managers, different results are obtained.

33:57.000 --> 34:10.000
Taylor decided that if we can find the patterns of the management,

34:10.000 --> 34:18.000
then these patterns significantly determine the final results that we strive for.

34:18.000 --> 34:24.000
In this regard, Taylor proposed the concept of scientific management.

34:25.000 --> 34:32.000
The fact is that what concerns the 19th century, in the 19th century there was a development of science,

34:32.000 --> 34:38.000
and therefore science emphasized the truthfulness, the resultiveness of the approach.

34:38.000 --> 34:47.000
From this point of view, Taylor introduced and formulated the system of organization of scientific management,

34:47.000 --> 34:54.000
or what became very well known as the scientific organization of labor.

34:54.000 --> 35:02.000
It is related to the name of Taylor, he introduced these positions in the 19th century.

35:03.000 --> 35:18.000
As for this approach, Taylor assumes that it is the administration that takes on the task of developing the scientific foundation of management.

35:18.000 --> 35:28.000
I, as the owner, will decide how the organization of labor interaction will be built,

35:28.000 --> 35:33.000
how the interaction with the manufacturers will be built, how the interaction with suppliers will be built.

35:33.000 --> 35:40.000
Moreover, if I want to get a result that suits me, I must base it on some scientific principles.

35:40.000 --> 35:45.000
The scientific principles of those that Taylor proposes in his research.

35:45.000 --> 35:49.000
As for Taylor, he left the practice.

35:49.000 --> 35:59.000
His achievements, his work was related to the fact that he observed the activities of workers,

35:59.000 --> 36:09.000
the activities of the leaders of these workers, and, accordingly, he identified those approaches, those methods,

36:09.000 --> 36:15.000
those actions that led to the desired results, and those actions that hindered the achievement of the result,

36:15.000 --> 36:26.000
that led to disorganization of production, that led to various difficulties and failure of certain plans.

36:26.000 --> 36:34.000
Taylor was based on these scientifically established facts,

36:34.000 --> 36:40.000
the facts that science has highlighted, science of the 19th century,

36:40.000 --> 36:45.000
and, in fact, the facts that Taylor called the scientific organization of labor.

36:45.000 --> 36:57.000
So, if the administration selects workers for production, for those or other machines, based on these scientific results,

36:57.000 --> 37:05.000
it will contribute to the achievement of the final result, for which the production is carried out.

37:05.000 --> 37:12.000
In the end, the owner invests money to get the desired return, to get profit,

37:12.000 --> 37:17.000
and, accordingly, to have the opportunity to expand the production to get even more profit.

37:17.000 --> 37:24.000
But it was Taylor who drew attention to the fact that it is not enough for us to simply select workers.

37:24.000 --> 37:30.000
It is not enough to select those who will work on machines.

37:30.000 --> 37:39.000
It is necessary to organize the training of these workers, first, and, secondly, to develop the abilities that each worker has.

37:39.000 --> 37:43.000
On a machine, you can work at different speeds.

37:43.000 --> 37:50.000
In the end, you can adapt to work on this machine in such a way to get more results,

37:50.000 --> 37:57.000
to get rid of trauma, to get rid of all sorts of difficulties that arise.

37:57.000 --> 38:01.000
To organize what today was called the safety technique.

38:01.000 --> 38:05.000
It also refers to Taylor, who drew attention to this.

38:05.000 --> 38:10.000
If our management system, our production management system,

38:10.000 --> 38:16.000
is organized in terms of adequate selection of employees,

38:16.000 --> 38:28.000
who will later be trained, and we train them, and develop them in terms of working in certain conditions,

38:28.000 --> 38:33.000
then we can be sure that we will not just get the desired result,

38:33.000 --> 38:39.000
but this result will even exceed our expectations.

38:40.000 --> 38:44.000
Taylor in the 19th century. This is very important.

38:44.000 --> 38:51.000
Today, many of Taylor's ideas, which I am talking about now, are obvious.

38:51.000 --> 38:57.000
They are already being studied in management from the very beginning.

38:57.000 --> 39:03.000
They are already given as the most obvious things, because otherwise it cannot be so.

39:03.000 --> 39:08.000
But this is today. Taylor received his results in the 19th century,

39:08.000 --> 39:14.000
when there was a completely different attitude to production and to the tasks that were faced,

39:14.000 --> 39:18.000
when capitalist and economic relations were only affirmed.

39:18.000 --> 39:25.000
So, from Taylor's point of view, if the administration, management,

39:25.000 --> 39:33.000
performs trustworthy cooperation with the workers in the direction of achieving certain goals,

39:33.000 --> 39:43.000
then we will get even better results.

39:43.000 --> 39:49.000
In this case, the task is to motivate the workers to work.

39:49.000 --> 39:56.000
Again, remember the management functions that we talked about.

39:56.000 --> 40:00.000
In fact, it is Taylor who pays attention to the need for motivation.

40:00.000 --> 40:06.000
But perhaps he was the first to bring all this into the system,

40:06.000 --> 40:10.000
because it is not for nothing that the scientific management begins with him.

40:11.000 --> 40:27.000
Finally, Taylor draws attention to the need to distribute responsibility between management and workers.

40:27.000 --> 40:31.000
Everyone is responsible for their own sector of activity.

40:31.000 --> 40:37.000
The workers are engaged in the performance of production, they produce something.

40:37.000 --> 40:45.000
And the administration is engaged in the management.

40:45.000 --> 40:49.000
But all this is very interconnected.

40:49.000 --> 40:57.000
It is pointless to lead by an unknown name and to perform something against the guidance.

40:57.000 --> 41:05.000
Only if the workers and the managers move in the same direction,

41:05.000 --> 41:12.000
if the executive and management functions of the workers and the responsibility of each of them for their own sector are distributed between them,

41:12.000 --> 41:19.000
only in this case, under these conditions, we can get the desired result.

41:19.000 --> 41:26.000
Let's say, Taylor's achievements were his achievements.

41:26.000 --> 41:31.000
And that is why Taylor is considered the father of scientific management.

41:31.000 --> 41:38.000
They all had practical applications and gave fast practical results.

41:38.000 --> 41:46.000
As for the 19th century, during this period of rapid industrial development,

41:46.000 --> 41:56.000
some phenomena arose that did not please the owners of enterprises.

41:56.000 --> 41:59.000
One of these phenomena is restrictionism.

41:59.000 --> 42:02.000
That is, working with a coolant.

42:02.000 --> 42:12.000
The worker comes and starts working at the machine, getting some results, but he does not show activity.

42:12.000 --> 42:25.000
He is on duty, and, accordingly, he has no initiative to work better,

42:25.000 --> 42:29.000
to do what was called a rationalization proposal,

42:29.000 --> 42:38.000
to use all the potential opportunities that a particular machine gives him.

42:38.000 --> 42:41.000
Again, pay attention to the fact that this is the 19th century.

42:41.000 --> 42:45.000
Machines are just emerging, they are modernizing,

42:45.000 --> 42:55.000
and, accordingly, there are no standards or prospects of this or that activity.

42:55.000 --> 42:59.000
And what does the worker want?

42:59.000 --> 43:04.000
The worker, of course, wants to be less busy, to get more.

43:04.000 --> 43:10.000
And that is why Taylor comes from the fact that this is the cause of restrictionism.

43:10.000 --> 43:16.000
In order to get rid of it, we must motivate the workers,

43:16.000 --> 43:19.000
we must organize planning correctly,

43:19.000 --> 43:26.000
and we must control every step of the implementation of this or that activity.

43:26.000 --> 43:30.000
So far, every step is a stop of management.

43:30.000 --> 43:36.000
Flexibility is the next stage of its development, which we will talk about later.

43:37.000 --> 43:41.000
As for Taylor, he not only explained the phenomenon of restrictionism,

43:41.000 --> 43:47.000
but also proposed ways to eliminate it, to overcome it, which worked.

43:47.000 --> 43:52.000
At those enterprises, at those factories where Taylor's scientific organization was implemented,

43:52.000 --> 44:01.000
the results were more than remarkable compared to other factories.

44:02.000 --> 44:09.000
As for Taylor, he also proposed a system of organizational measures,

44:09.000 --> 44:15.000
which was aimed at improving the results, improving the production.

44:15.000 --> 44:22.000
He introduced chronometry, which is a time measurement necessary for each operation.

44:22.000 --> 44:30.000
Taylor was the person who proposed to divide the process of work on the machine

44:30.000 --> 44:40.000
into specific operational stages, to measure the time that the worker spends on each operation,

44:40.000 --> 44:45.000
and then to see which of these operations slows down the final activity,

44:45.000 --> 44:49.000
where the worker needs assistants, where something needs to be changed,

44:49.000 --> 44:52.000
where some changes in the machine itself can be made.

44:52.000 --> 44:58.000
This chronometry, or what is now called a work time photo,

44:58.000 --> 45:01.000
is all that was proposed by Taylor.

45:01.000 --> 45:05.000
Taylor also proposed to introduce instruction cards,

45:05.000 --> 45:09.000
that is, in fact, what is now called a safety technique.

45:10.000 --> 45:24.000
You come to work, and the first thing you are given is a list of actions that you must perform,

45:24.000 --> 45:27.000
that you must not perform.

45:27.000 --> 45:33.000
In fact, these are instructions that ensure, on the one hand,

45:33.000 --> 45:36.000
the preservation of your life and health, as a safety technique,

45:36.000 --> 45:44.000
and on the other hand, the preservation of equipment and the increase of the results of production,

45:44.000 --> 45:49.000
in terms of production, in terms of the supply of services.

45:49.000 --> 45:55.000
Taylor proposed to create so-called planning offices,

45:55.000 --> 46:02.000
which would plan the work of people on certain technical means.

46:02.000 --> 46:06.000
It would be easier to work on some machines,

46:06.000 --> 46:08.000
because there are simpler operations,

46:08.000 --> 46:13.000
and some machines are associated with more complex tasks, with greater complexity.

46:13.000 --> 46:16.000
So what happened very often?

46:16.000 --> 46:20.000
A huge number of blanks accumulated after some machines,

46:20.000 --> 46:26.000
which the workers, in other words, simply did not have time to process.

46:26.000 --> 46:30.000
It was the planning offices that were recognized in order to match the number of machines.

46:30.000 --> 46:36.000
If, for example, one machine gives 100 blanks in an hour,

46:36.000 --> 46:40.000
and the second machine, processing this blank after the first machine,

46:40.000 --> 46:44.000
is able to process only 50 parts in an hour,

46:44.000 --> 46:46.000
let's put two machines.

46:46.000 --> 46:52.000
And accordingly, then two machines will be able to work with the same 100 parts.

46:52.000 --> 46:54.000
There will be no stoppage of the previous machines.

46:54.000 --> 46:57.000
These are all the tasks that were solved by the planning office.

46:57.000 --> 47:02.000
And in fact, today it all exists as a matter of course.

47:02.000 --> 47:06.000
But at the time when Taylor proposed it, when Taylor implemented it,

47:06.000 --> 47:14.000
these were the methods that contributed to the colossal rise of the results

47:14.000 --> 47:17.000
that were at those factories.

47:17.000 --> 47:24.000
So, this is what concerns scientific management or the formation of management.

47:24.000 --> 47:27.000
This is what concerns Taylor's contribution.

47:27.000 --> 47:34.000
And in fact, he is considered the father of modern management.

47:34.000 --> 47:40.000
Because almost all the ideas that we talked about today,

47:40.000 --> 47:43.000
are what are used now.

47:43.000 --> 47:46.000
This is what is already perceived without a doubt.

47:46.000 --> 47:54.000
At the time, 100 years ago, Taylor had to make a lot of effort

47:54.000 --> 48:04.000
to prove to the owners of those or other factories the need for these changes.

48:04.000 --> 48:10.000
After all, all this at one time was a serious investment in additional production.

48:11.000 --> 48:22.000
Naturally, the capitalist is interested in investing only if he is confident in the return.

48:22.000 --> 48:30.000
What Taylor proposed, in fact, were many points related to the work with the staff.

48:30.000 --> 48:37.000
At that time, in the 19th century, working with the staff was not yet something significant.

48:37.000 --> 48:41.000
And it was believed that the main thing was technical support.

48:41.000 --> 48:43.000
We will always find people.

48:43.000 --> 48:51.000
In fact, it was Taylor who made the first impact on this idea.

48:51.000 --> 49:00.000
He can also be considered the founder of various concepts of management and human resources.

49:01.000 --> 49:10.000
The implementation of Taylor's scientific management ideas took 30-40 years.

49:10.000 --> 49:16.000
Gradually, they were introduced into production.

49:16.000 --> 49:22.000
Gradually, they began to dominate both in Europe and in America.

49:23.000 --> 49:32.000
But at the same time, it became obvious that the results Taylor got in the late 19th and early 20th centuries

49:32.000 --> 49:38.000
were not quite adequate.

49:38.000 --> 49:45.000
After all, they required an update in the early 20th century.

49:46.000 --> 49:52.000
Because the administration itself changed, the production itself changed,

49:52.000 --> 49:59.000
the people who work in the production changed, the social-economic relations changed,

49:59.000 --> 50:06.000
the social-technical systems that exist changed,

50:06.000 --> 50:10.000
the requirements for the specific results that were obtained changed.

50:10.000 --> 50:17.000
And the need for an expansion of the concept of management,

50:17.000 --> 50:23.000
further development of Taylor's ideas, not to abandon them.

50:23.000 --> 50:28.000
These are very important aspects that I have already addressed and again draw your attention to.

50:28.000 --> 50:36.000
Not to abandon Taylor's ideas, that is, time has passed, they have worked out their own, now they need to be replaced.

50:36.000 --> 50:43.000
Not to replace, but to add those or other concepts, to modernize those or other approaches,

50:43.000 --> 50:48.000
to change the terminology, to change the requirements, to change the tasks, to change the conditions.

50:48.000 --> 50:54.000
And this was implemented in the classical school of management.

50:54.000 --> 50:59.000
As for Taylor, it is a school of scientific management,

50:59.000 --> 51:09.000
because he set the task of achieving a scientific justification for the concept of management.

51:09.000 --> 51:18.000
Now, after he set this task and decided, and scientific management was introduced into production,

51:18.000 --> 51:24.000
the next school emerged, or the school of classical management.

51:25.000 --> 51:36.000
Classical, because this school emerged at the stage of a fairly widely developed capitalist production,

51:36.000 --> 51:38.000
capitalist economic relations.

51:38.000 --> 51:48.000
And, accordingly, those ideas, those approaches, those principles that were laid down in the classical school,

51:48.000 --> 51:52.000
that were based on Taylor's scientific management,

51:52.000 --> 51:59.000
are the foundations on which any system of existing management is built today.

51:59.000 --> 52:04.000
This is a classic in the sense that it is an idea that justified itself and its approach.

52:04.000 --> 52:12.000
The development of the classical school was associated with different names,

52:12.000 --> 52:20.000
but both the scientific management associated with Taylor and the classical school associated with Foyol,

52:20.000 --> 52:25.000
who developed the classical principles of management.

52:25.000 --> 52:28.000
Or the principles of classical management.

52:28.000 --> 52:36.000
This is what is written in any textbook today, and in almost every book that is offered to you in the list of literature,

52:36.000 --> 52:41.000
you will come across both Taylor and Foyol, and the principles that are laid down there.

52:41.000 --> 52:47.000
Again, as for Foyol, he highlighted many principles.

52:47.000 --> 53:01.000
In our discussion and analysis today, we will focus on those principles that are as relevant today,

53:01.000 --> 53:11.000
or even more relevant than they were 100 years ago, when Foyol highlighted them, considered them, justified them, and implemented them.

53:11.000 --> 53:25.000
As for the classical principles of management, Foyol is associated with the idea of division of labor.

53:26.000 --> 53:38.000
We should not strive for working universals that can do any operation, any detail.

53:38.000 --> 53:51.000
As the growth of production, as the growth of other production activities is getting more and more complicated,

53:51.000 --> 53:58.000
we need what is called narrow professionalism.

53:58.000 --> 54:07.000
We need division of labor in such a way that certain operations are performed professionally.

54:07.000 --> 54:13.000
This idea was proposed and considered by Foyol, and it was implemented.

54:13.000 --> 54:20.000
This is why the emphasis was placed on the idea of universality, so that each worker could replace another.

54:20.000 --> 54:29.000
Foyol noticed that this is good, but in the end it turns out that we can replace another,

54:29.000 --> 54:41.000
but this is achieved by losing certain qualities, certain speed, certain time in each production site.

54:41.000 --> 54:47.000
If we divide all production into component parts, into component operations,

54:47.000 --> 54:55.000
and we orient workers to professional mastering of narrow sites,

54:55.000 --> 54:59.000
then in the end, when the composition of certain parts takes place,

54:59.000 --> 55:07.000
we will get a much better quality result, which will have a higher value.

55:07.000 --> 55:13.000
The next principle of management, which Foyol highlights, concerns power and responsibility.

55:13.000 --> 55:16.000
In this case, power is understood as control.

55:16.000 --> 55:21.000
Again, let's recall the management functions that we discussed.

55:21.000 --> 55:27.000
But it was Foyol who noticed that the management power,

55:27.000 --> 55:31.000
that is, the control function of management, implies responsibility.

55:31.000 --> 55:38.000
Because there is a goal of an activity, there is a path to its achievement.

55:38.000 --> 55:45.000
The task of a manager is to control the movement to this goal,

55:45.000 --> 55:51.000
but it cannot be controlled formally, in general terms.

55:51.000 --> 55:56.000
If I control a certain process,

55:56.000 --> 56:02.000
then I take responsibility for the fact that the organization of this process

56:02.000 --> 56:08.000
should give the intermediate results, which will eventually lead to the final result.

56:08.000 --> 56:14.000
Again, today this is an obvious thing, but in the days of Foyol,

56:14.000 --> 56:17.000
it was precisely the power that was discussed as control.

56:17.000 --> 56:24.000
And the manager should not be responsible, he should simply control.

56:24.000 --> 56:27.000
And what are the results of this control?

56:27.000 --> 56:31.000
What are the results of the management decisions that are made?

56:31.000 --> 56:34.000
This is what he did not pay attention to.

56:34.000 --> 56:40.000
But Foyol concluded that power should not be for the sake of power.

56:40.000 --> 56:44.000
I am a manager, and therefore I manage.

56:44.000 --> 56:47.000
But power should be for the sake of the final result,

56:47.000 --> 56:51.000
for the sake of the intermediate result, to achieve the final result.

56:51.000 --> 56:56.000
And accordingly, the manager takes responsibility

56:56.000 --> 57:01.000
for achieving the results that he controls.

57:01.000 --> 57:04.000
The next principle of management is discipline.

57:04.000 --> 57:07.000
I don't think that anything should be added here.

57:07.000 --> 57:10.000
Besides, when Foyol talked about discipline,

57:10.000 --> 57:13.000
in the early 20th century, Foyol,

57:13.000 --> 57:20.000
discipline was, again, only for the lower level,

57:20.000 --> 57:23.000
for the linear employees, for the workers.

57:23.000 --> 57:27.000
So Foyol drew attention to the fact that discipline is not only

57:27.000 --> 57:32.000
what the workers should do, but also what concerns the managers themselves.

57:32.000 --> 57:36.000
That is, the manager should also obey discipline,

57:36.000 --> 57:38.000
the management discipline.

57:38.000 --> 57:41.000
And this just means, depending on the previous point,

57:41.000 --> 57:46.000
that the manager takes responsibility for the results he gives.

57:46.000 --> 57:52.000
And this is where the idea of giving an example comes from.

57:52.000 --> 57:59.000
In the sense that depending on how the manager behaves,

57:59.000 --> 58:03.000
it determines the attitude towards him,

58:03.000 --> 58:08.000
and most importantly, the final results that his management activity will have.

58:08.000 --> 58:11.000
The next principle is the principle of initiation.

58:11.000 --> 58:14.000
A very important principle, and it concerns...

58:14.000 --> 58:17.000
Of course, this principle was transferred from the military order,

58:17.000 --> 58:23.000
but Foyol drew attention to the biggest trouble of production.

58:23.000 --> 58:26.000
Again, as for Foyol, this is the beginning of the 20th century,

58:26.000 --> 58:29.000
and he was engaged in more production,

58:29.000 --> 58:32.000
production of some material products, but not services.

58:32.000 --> 58:36.000
Although, again, all those principles that we are now considering

58:36.000 --> 58:41.000
are applicable to the management of the services.

58:41.000 --> 58:44.000
So, as for Foyol, he drew attention to the fact that

58:44.000 --> 58:51.000
the biggest trouble of production is that there are a lot of managers.

58:51.000 --> 58:57.000
The director of the plant, his deputy, department managers,

58:57.000 --> 59:01.000
managers of management, managers of workshops, managers of shifts,

59:01.000 --> 59:03.000
managers of the district, and so on.

59:03.000 --> 59:09.000
Everyone wants to manage, everyone wants to show their power as a control,

59:09.000 --> 59:18.000
and, accordingly, it often turns out that people give contradictory orders.

59:18.000 --> 59:26.000
And, accordingly, there is a problem of how to combine all this into a single whole.

59:26.000 --> 59:29.000
That is why Foyol drew attention to the fact that

59:29.000 --> 59:35.000
there should be a single principle, and at the same time,

59:35.000 --> 59:41.000
the next principle is that there should be a certain line of power.

59:41.000 --> 59:46.000
As they say today, it is fashionable to call it the vertical power.

59:46.000 --> 59:50.000
Foyol called it the line of power, or, since it was about production,

59:50.000 --> 59:54.000
since it was about scientific approach to management,

59:54.000 --> 59:57.000
he called it the scalar chain.

59:57.000 --> 01:00:01.000
The scalar chain is a sequence of elements.

01:00:01.000 --> 01:00:07.000
Each subsequent element should be oriented to what is in front of it.

01:00:07.000 --> 01:00:12.000
This is the principle that Foyol and his mechanism speak about.

01:00:12.000 --> 01:00:19.000
The common goal is set, and then different lower-rank managers

01:00:19.000 --> 01:00:26.000
get their task within the framework of achieving the common goal.

01:00:26.000 --> 01:00:31.000
And within these frameworks, you can act relatively freely.

01:00:31.000 --> 01:00:35.000
But your higher-rank manager should make sure that you,

01:00:35.000 --> 01:00:38.000
first of all, do not go beyond these frameworks,

01:00:38.000 --> 01:00:44.000
otherwise you will invade the sphere of action of another unit, another manager.

01:00:44.000 --> 01:00:51.000
And, on the other hand, the final result that you get

01:00:51.000 --> 01:00:58.000
is the necessary intermediate part of the final result

01:00:58.000 --> 01:01:01.000
for which the production is organized.

01:01:01.000 --> 01:01:07.000
The next point Foyol addressed has become very popular today.

01:01:07.000 --> 01:01:11.000
Foyol called it the unity of leadership.

01:01:11.000 --> 01:01:18.000
In fact, today this idea is called the unity of the team of managers,

01:01:18.000 --> 01:01:24.000
or the unity of the top management,

01:01:24.000 --> 01:01:30.000
depending on the sphere, the area of action in which it is spread.

01:01:30.000 --> 01:01:36.000
Foyol drew attention to the fact that in the beginning it is important,

01:01:36.000 --> 01:01:42.000
but the situation is much worse when there is no agreement among the higher management.

01:01:42.000 --> 01:01:46.000
The higher management is responsible for very large production areas.

01:01:46.000 --> 01:01:50.000
The head of the site is responsible for the work of 5-10 machines.

01:01:50.000 --> 01:01:52.000
We have thousands of machines.

01:01:52.000 --> 01:01:57.000
Of course, some chaos will appear if he starts to engage in his own activity,

01:01:57.000 --> 01:02:01.000
but still, this is not a catastrophic chaos.

01:02:01.000 --> 01:02:07.000
If a disagreement appears at the highest level,

01:02:07.000 --> 01:02:14.000
then there may be difficulties between two rather serious parts of the business,

01:02:14.000 --> 01:02:22.000
which will definitely lead to the breakdown of all existing systems and relations.

01:02:22.000 --> 01:02:29.000
As a result, we will get not what we wanted, if we get anything at all.

01:02:29.000 --> 01:02:34.000
As you can see, Foyol looked ahead for almost 50 years.

01:02:34.000 --> 01:02:38.000
This is shown in the table we looked at.

01:02:38.000 --> 01:02:46.000
The next point Foyol highlights is the subordination of personal interests to the common.

01:02:46.000 --> 01:02:50.000
Again, this is an obvious point.

01:02:50.000 --> 01:02:58.000
The fact is that every person has his own tasks, interests and approaches.

01:02:58.000 --> 01:03:07.000
But he came to the organization, to the company, which implements certain tasks.

01:03:07.000 --> 01:03:15.000
And here you have to integrate your individual qualities into the common goal.

01:03:15.000 --> 01:03:20.000
In fact, in this case, Foyol is running very far ahead.

01:03:20.000 --> 01:03:27.000
This subordination of personal interests to the common is what is called team building today.

01:03:27.000 --> 01:03:30.000
This is very much in demand.

01:03:30.000 --> 01:03:34.000
Moreover, the wider the production area, the more people are engaged in it,

01:03:34.000 --> 01:03:37.000
the more important is the issue of team building.

01:03:37.000 --> 01:03:43.000
Foyol, like Taylor, again came from the practice.

01:03:43.000 --> 01:03:49.000
He was engaged in analysis and study of work in large enterprises and factories.

01:03:49.000 --> 01:03:54.000
He drew attention to the fact that if there is a problem of unity,

01:03:54.000 --> 01:04:00.000
if there is a common goal that is shared by the workers,

01:04:00.000 --> 01:04:03.000
the results are much better.

01:04:03.000 --> 01:04:06.000
This is a very important result of Foyol,

01:04:06.000 --> 01:04:14.000
because it will be the basis of the next direction of the school of human relations.

01:04:14.000 --> 01:04:19.000
But again, Taylor also talked about this.

01:04:19.000 --> 01:04:26.000
Foyol just highlighted this situation and brought it to the foundation.

01:04:26.000 --> 01:04:33.000
The next principle that is important for management in Foyol is the reward of staff.

01:04:33.000 --> 01:04:37.000
Foyol, of course, talks about the material reward.

01:04:37.000 --> 01:04:43.000
If you have achieved the plan, you will receive the appropriate reward.

01:04:43.000 --> 01:04:47.000
If you have overcompleted the plan, you will receive the appropriate reward.

01:04:47.000 --> 01:04:54.000
If you have not completed the plan, there should be some sanctions and fines.

01:04:54.000 --> 01:04:57.000
But again, we need to figure it out.

01:04:57.000 --> 01:05:00.000
Foyol highlighted the reason for not completing the plan.

01:05:00.000 --> 01:05:05.000
Maybe the plan was overcompleted, and it was not your fault.

01:05:05.000 --> 01:05:08.000
It was the wrong management who planned it.

01:05:08.000 --> 01:05:13.000
Then you should be punished, but not you, but the managers who planned it.

01:05:13.000 --> 01:05:19.000
So, the reward problem is what we call material stimulation today.

01:05:19.000 --> 01:05:23.000
Foyol, of course, talked about material stimulation.

01:05:23.000 --> 01:05:31.000
But, as Taylor, Foyol also pointed out that not everything is measured by material stimulation.

01:05:31.000 --> 01:05:41.000
In fact, Foyol's approaches in his management methods include protection, including non-material stimulation.

01:05:41.000 --> 01:05:46.000
Again, this should not be surprised, because what concerns Taylor, Foyol and other authors,

01:05:46.000 --> 01:05:54.000
about whom we will talk today, they did not create their approaches from the head, not from theory, but from practice.

01:05:54.000 --> 01:06:00.000
And that's why they left their name in the history of management,

01:06:00.000 --> 01:06:08.000
that they were able to capture the main points that arise.

01:06:09.000 --> 01:06:12.000
In addition to material stimulation, a person is interested in reward,

01:06:12.000 --> 01:06:16.000
and not always in a purely monetary way.

01:06:16.000 --> 01:06:18.000
The same authority, the same respect.

01:06:18.000 --> 01:06:23.000
Foyol noted this, but still, the majority of people do it on material stimulation.

01:06:23.000 --> 01:06:30.000
The next principle that Foyol talks about is the centralization of management.

01:06:30.000 --> 01:06:32.000
An important principle from which point of view?

01:06:32.000 --> 01:06:39.000
Foyol noticed that very often managers become too many.

01:06:39.000 --> 01:06:47.000
And, of course, every person thinks of himself as a boss, feels power as control, forgets about responsibility.

01:06:47.000 --> 01:06:55.000
And the problem arises that there are too many bosses, and it's difficult to negotiate with each other.

01:06:55.000 --> 01:07:02.000
And the boss has his tasks, his managerial functions, not just executive.

01:07:02.000 --> 01:07:09.000
And in this regard, the abundance of leadership, the abundance of managers is the starting point

01:07:09.000 --> 01:07:19.000
that can lead to a split within the business.

01:07:19.000 --> 01:07:25.000
That's why Foyol says that a centralized management system should be built

01:07:25.000 --> 01:07:31.000
in order to get rid of extra managers, of extra workers, of the saving of jobs.

01:07:31.000 --> 01:07:34.000
This is the problem that was solved a long time ago.

01:07:34.000 --> 01:07:38.000
This is what Taylor was doing, creating his chronometry, creating his instructions.

01:07:38.000 --> 01:07:45.000
And the task was that the less we hire workers, the less we pay, the more profit we have at the output.

01:07:45.000 --> 01:07:48.000
Foyol set the same task for the applicant managers.

01:07:48.000 --> 01:07:53.000
The more managers, the bigger the problem.

01:07:53.000 --> 01:08:00.000
That's why we need to find an optimal number of managers, depending on the volume of production,

01:08:00.000 --> 01:08:02.000
depending on the tasks that are set.

01:08:02.000 --> 01:08:07.000
And in every particular case, which Foyol considered in every particular factory,

01:08:07.000 --> 01:08:09.000
he calculated the corresponding results.

01:08:09.000 --> 01:08:15.000
The next thing Foyol paid attention to was the principle of justice.

01:08:15.000 --> 01:08:24.000
There are different theories of motivation, including the theory of justice,

01:08:24.000 --> 01:08:32.000
which is that the same work should get the same reward.

01:08:32.000 --> 01:08:40.000
That is, it shouldn't be that two people do the same work, get the same results,

01:08:40.000 --> 01:08:46.000
but get a two or three times higher material reward.

01:08:46.000 --> 01:08:58.000
Foyol paid attention to the fact that people are very sensitive to the fair attitude to themselves.

01:08:58.000 --> 01:09:04.000
If I make some efforts, if I make any actions,

01:09:04.000 --> 01:09:13.000
I want these actions to be noticed, approved, so that my initiative is in demand,

01:09:13.000 --> 01:09:16.000
my initiative gets a certain rating.

01:09:16.000 --> 01:09:28.000
In this regard, Foyol paid attention to the fact that the reward for the work should be fair.

01:09:28.000 --> 01:09:37.000
In the sense that for the same results, for the same actions, we should get the same reward.

01:09:37.000 --> 01:09:46.000
In addition, Foyol paid attention to the need for order in official duties.

01:09:46.000 --> 01:09:53.000
That is, Foyol says that when a person comes to work,

01:09:53.000 --> 01:10:00.000
whether he is a worker or a manager, he should be familiar with his official duties.

01:10:00.000 --> 01:10:08.000
What are his duties, what will he be asked for, and what rights does he have?

01:10:08.000 --> 01:10:11.000
What right does he have to ask?

01:10:11.000 --> 01:10:17.000
It is not possible for a person to come to work, or rather to a managerial job,

01:10:17.000 --> 01:10:24.000
and not know the limits of his authority,

01:10:24.000 --> 01:10:33.000
not know the sphere of influence he has the right to exert,

01:10:33.000 --> 01:10:38.000
and where the limits of responsibility of another person are.

01:10:39.000 --> 01:10:47.000
In order to avoid misunderstandings, scandals, and divisions between managers,

01:10:47.000 --> 01:10:53.000
there should be order, that is, there should be regulations in the sphere of actions,

01:10:53.000 --> 01:10:57.000
in the sphere of responsibility of each manager, for which he is responsible.

01:10:57.000 --> 01:11:03.000
The next principle that Foyol highlights

01:11:03.000 --> 01:11:11.000
is that it is necessary to ensure the stability of the workplace for the staff.

01:11:11.000 --> 01:11:17.000
This is what is characterized by the phrase confidence in the future.

01:11:17.000 --> 01:11:22.000
I am a manager, I am a manager, a professional in my field.

01:11:22.000 --> 01:11:27.000
I was hired to work for an organization of some business processes.

01:11:28.000 --> 01:11:34.000
At the same time, I must be sure that this is not a temporary organization for me,

01:11:34.000 --> 01:11:38.000
that this is the organization in which I will continue to work.

01:11:38.000 --> 01:11:44.000
If I start to cope successfully with the tasks I am assigned,

01:11:44.000 --> 01:11:50.000
it will ensure my career growth as a manager.

01:11:51.000 --> 01:11:54.000
Accordingly, the stability of the workplace leads to the fact

01:11:54.000 --> 01:12:01.000
that I will be interested in working in this company, in working informally.

01:12:01.000 --> 01:12:08.000
If I consider it as a temporary place, or I do not associate with this company

01:12:08.000 --> 01:12:13.000
the principal ideas and views of my future,

01:12:13.000 --> 01:12:16.000
then my attitude to work will be appropriate.

01:12:17.000 --> 01:12:23.000
At the same time, Foyol draws attention to the need to cultivate initiatives.

01:12:23.000 --> 01:12:27.000
Initiatives not only for the workers, but also for the managers.

01:12:27.000 --> 01:12:32.000
Again, with all the restrictions that we talked about,

01:12:32.000 --> 01:12:38.000
both in the presence of a single beginning and in the presence of a scalar chain of management,

01:12:38.000 --> 01:12:44.000
in this case it is about the fact that there is a sphere for which I am responsible.

01:12:44.000 --> 01:12:48.000
And in this sphere I can carry out an initiative,

01:12:48.000 --> 01:12:51.000
I can optimize the working conditions,

01:12:51.000 --> 01:13:00.000
I can make some rationalization proposals that, in my opinion, will lead to improvement of the results.

01:13:00.000 --> 01:13:07.000
But Foyol emphasizes that any initiative must be responsible.

01:13:07.000 --> 01:13:11.000
For example, there is already a certain established production process.

01:13:12.000 --> 01:13:19.000
I make changes, thereby I change and violate the existing system.

01:13:19.000 --> 01:13:25.000
Of course, the result can be much better, and then my initiative will be justified.

01:13:25.000 --> 01:13:29.000
But on the other hand, my initiative may not be justified enough.

01:13:29.000 --> 01:13:34.000
And in this sense, the introduction of changes in the production process leads to a failure of production.

01:13:34.000 --> 01:13:38.000
So, the initiative must have reasonable limits.

01:13:39.000 --> 01:13:45.000
And again, as for this initiative, it must be implemented taking into account all the tasks,

01:13:45.000 --> 01:13:49.000
all the principles that are before production.

01:13:49.000 --> 01:13:57.000
Well, another point that Foyol highlights and that should be stopped

01:13:57.000 --> 01:14:02.000
is what Foyol himself calls the corporate spirit.

01:14:02.000 --> 01:14:07.000
Here again Foyol jumps very far ahead.

01:14:07.000 --> 01:14:12.000
Because at the beginning of the 21st century, in our modern business,

01:14:12.000 --> 01:14:18.000
the corporate spirit is the education that is worth the price.

01:14:18.000 --> 01:14:25.000
It is loyalty to the staff, it is the creation of a staff reserve,

01:14:25.000 --> 01:14:30.000
it is the provision of staff growth within the organization,

01:14:30.000 --> 01:14:35.000
it is the team formation, it is the unity of the team.

01:14:35.000 --> 01:14:41.000
It is all the corporate events, corporate meetings, corporate trips.

01:14:41.000 --> 01:14:45.000
It is all that creates a certain corporate spirit.

01:14:45.000 --> 01:14:50.000
It is all that is hidden under the brand of a particular company.

01:14:50.000 --> 01:15:00.000
And the main idea here is that the emphasis is on the attitude of the company to the person.

01:15:00.000 --> 01:15:04.000
A person ceases to be a simple screw.

01:15:04.000 --> 01:15:08.000
A person realizes his importance and importance in the company.

01:15:08.000 --> 01:15:12.000
He understands that his experience is valued.

01:15:12.000 --> 01:15:16.000
And if it is appreciated, if it is noticed,

01:15:16.000 --> 01:15:20.000
a person is naturally interested in the further application,

01:15:20.000 --> 01:15:27.000
in the further development of his abilities within the framework of this company.

01:15:28.000 --> 01:15:32.000
Of course, Fayol did not describe all this in detail.

01:15:32.000 --> 01:15:36.000
But the general idea of this corporate spirit,

01:15:36.000 --> 01:15:44.000
laid down by Fayol in the 1920s,

01:15:44.000 --> 01:15:47.000
has found a wide range of distribution,

01:15:47.000 --> 01:15:53.000
both today and in the subsequent development of the classical management school.

01:15:53.000 --> 01:16:00.000
In principle, Taylor also talked about this, but he said in general terms.

01:16:00.000 --> 01:16:03.000
Fayol formulates this more specifically.

01:16:03.000 --> 01:16:09.000
And Fayol begins to introduce this corporate spirit into production,

01:16:09.000 --> 01:16:11.000
creating different kinds of working groups.

01:16:11.000 --> 01:16:15.000
And then, when we talk about modern tenancy management,

01:16:15.000 --> 01:16:18.000
we will stop at the corporate spirit separately.

01:16:19.000 --> 01:16:25.000
But it comes up to Fayol as a person who began to introduce this

01:16:25.000 --> 01:16:29.000
and apply it in different areas of management.

01:16:29.000 --> 01:16:35.000
Again, I think these principles are enough to understand

01:16:35.000 --> 01:16:38.000
the basic positions of the classical direction.

01:16:38.000 --> 01:16:40.000
There may be others.

01:16:40.000 --> 01:16:45.000
But you can familiarize yourself with them in the literature proposed.

01:16:45.000 --> 01:16:49.000
These are the principles that have a significant impact

01:16:49.000 --> 01:16:52.000
and influence on the modern state of management.

01:16:52.000 --> 01:17:01.000
The next school, which is a natural continuation of the classical ideas of Fayol,

01:17:01.000 --> 01:17:04.000
is the so-called school of human relations.

01:17:04.000 --> 01:17:13.000
Look, as we list the principles we have just discussed,

01:17:13.000 --> 01:17:21.000
we see that, having begun subjective management, responsibility, economic results,

01:17:21.000 --> 01:17:28.000
Fayol is getting closer and closer to taking into account subjective or human factors.

01:17:28.000 --> 01:17:38.000
In fact, Fayol prepares the ground for management

01:17:38.000 --> 01:17:46.000
and pays more attention to the human qualities and human traits of the employees,

01:17:46.000 --> 01:17:49.000
the staff they manage.

01:17:49.000 --> 01:17:54.000
Again, we should pay attention to the fact that the school of human relations

01:17:54.000 --> 01:17:57.000
has been developing since the 1930s,

01:17:57.000 --> 01:18:02.000
almost in parallel with the classical Fayol school.

01:18:02.000 --> 01:18:08.000
If we go back to the slide about the evolution of the management thought of the modern age,

01:18:08.000 --> 01:18:12.000
we see that the difference appears at the age of 15.

01:18:12.000 --> 01:18:18.000
But the classical school and the school of human relations are practically in sync.

01:18:18.000 --> 01:18:26.000
The classical school dealt with the problem of management as such,

01:18:27.000 --> 01:18:30.000
from the point of view of managing the results of the system,

01:18:30.000 --> 01:18:36.000
social-economic, social-technical systems, and obtaining the final result.

01:18:36.000 --> 01:18:38.000
As for the school of human relations,

01:18:38.000 --> 01:18:46.000
it actually focuses its main attention on people, on staff,

01:18:46.000 --> 01:18:49.000
on those human, subjective, passionate, qualitative, ambitious desires,

01:18:49.000 --> 01:18:54.000
opportunities that a person has to achieve the final result.

01:18:54.000 --> 01:18:58.000
But the school of human relations in management

01:18:58.000 --> 01:19:04.000
is concerned with the development of the system of relationships between people

01:19:04.000 --> 01:19:06.000
and the management of this system.

01:19:06.000 --> 01:19:11.000
As for the school of human relations,

01:19:11.000 --> 01:19:17.000
its development begins with the famous Hathorov experiments,

01:19:17.000 --> 01:19:27.000
which were conducted at the Western Electric plant in America, in the city of Hathorov, starting in 1927.

01:19:27.000 --> 01:19:32.000
This experiment was conducted by a large group of scientists,

01:19:32.000 --> 01:19:37.000
among them were Fritz Lisberger, Elton Mayo, Edith Dickson, and others.

01:19:37.000 --> 01:19:43.000
But usually this field is associated with the name Mayo.

01:19:44.000 --> 01:19:47.000
Although, maybe this is not entirely fair,

01:19:47.000 --> 01:19:54.000
because Mayo was one of the participants who did a lot,

01:19:54.000 --> 01:19:58.000
but still one of the organizers of this department was Fritz Lisberger.

01:19:58.000 --> 01:20:02.000
However, I think this is already a recognition of the merit of priorities,

01:20:02.000 --> 01:20:06.000
which is more important for the academic tradition.

01:20:06.000 --> 01:20:09.000
We are interested in the results.

01:20:09.000 --> 01:20:16.000
As for the results obtained during the Hathorov experiments,

01:20:16.000 --> 01:20:26.000
it was proven and demonstrated that when we deal with economic relations,

01:20:26.000 --> 01:20:29.000
when we deal with the management system,

01:20:29.000 --> 01:20:34.000
objective indicators play a significant role.

01:20:34.000 --> 01:20:37.000
And when we deal with business, we should, of course,

01:20:37.000 --> 01:20:40.000
be significantly more focused on objective indicators.

01:20:40.000 --> 01:20:44.000
We are interested in the economic results we have obtained.

01:20:44.000 --> 01:20:49.000
We are interested in our place in the market.

01:20:49.000 --> 01:20:53.000
We are interested in how the investments we have made have been repaid.

01:20:53.000 --> 01:20:56.000
But this is the result.

01:20:56.000 --> 01:21:02.000
This result is realized during a certain process.

01:21:02.000 --> 01:21:07.000
The production process, the service delivery process,

01:21:07.000 --> 01:21:10.000
the organization itself,

01:21:10.000 --> 01:21:15.000
and the same people, the same staff,

01:21:15.000 --> 01:21:18.000
the managers, take part in this process.

01:21:18.000 --> 01:21:22.000
And as for this school,

01:21:22.000 --> 01:21:26.000
the main focus in this case was on the fact that

01:21:27.000 --> 01:21:32.000
in addition to the formal organization,

01:21:32.000 --> 01:21:35.000
I am the manager, you are my subordinate,

01:21:35.000 --> 01:21:38.000
you should perform my tasks,

01:21:38.000 --> 01:21:42.000
there is also the informal relationship,

01:21:42.000 --> 01:21:44.000
the informal organization,

01:21:44.000 --> 01:21:52.000
which is often much more significant,

01:21:52.000 --> 01:21:55.000
much more important,

01:21:55.000 --> 01:21:58.000
much more perceptive,

01:21:58.000 --> 01:22:02.000
and much more significant for the final result

01:22:02.000 --> 01:22:05.000
than the whole structure of the formal organization.

01:22:05.000 --> 01:22:07.000
People work,

01:22:07.000 --> 01:22:09.000
and people work,

01:22:09.000 --> 01:22:12.000
and an informal relationship arises between them.

01:22:12.000 --> 01:22:16.000
You can formally sit from 9 to 6,

01:22:16.000 --> 01:22:20.000
and at the same time you can get a much better result,

01:22:20.000 --> 01:22:22.000
depending on your motivation,

01:22:22.000 --> 01:22:24.000
your desire, your needs,

01:22:24.000 --> 01:22:26.000
your loyalty,

01:22:26.000 --> 01:22:29.000
your prospects that you see in this organization

01:22:29.000 --> 01:22:31.000
or in the organization of competitors.

01:22:31.000 --> 01:22:33.000
And accordingly,

01:22:33.000 --> 01:22:36.000
the motivation of your activities that arise in you

01:22:36.000 --> 01:22:41.000
largely depends on the subjective features of a person.

01:22:41.000 --> 01:22:49.000
We formulated it as a classical doctrine of human relations.

01:22:49.000 --> 01:22:54.000
Everything I just said is related to this doctrine.

01:22:54.000 --> 01:22:59.000
And being a psychologist, a social psychologist,

01:22:59.000 --> 01:23:07.000
we found that the main feature of any organization,

01:23:07.000 --> 01:23:10.000
the main driving force of any organization

01:23:10.000 --> 01:23:13.000
is the people who work in it

01:23:13.000 --> 01:23:18.000
and the relations between people in this organization.

01:23:18.000 --> 01:23:23.000
If these are cooperative relations,

01:23:23.000 --> 01:23:26.000
positive relations,

01:23:26.000 --> 01:23:29.000
then the results will be significant,

01:23:29.000 --> 01:23:34.000
and the criteria that will be obtained will also be excellent.

01:23:34.000 --> 01:23:39.000
If these relations are competitive, aggressive, conflictive,

01:23:39.000 --> 01:23:45.000
then whatever investments you make in production,

01:23:45.000 --> 01:23:49.000
whatever modern equipment you buy,

01:23:49.000 --> 01:23:54.000
you will not get results that are significantly different from the results of competitors.

01:23:54.000 --> 01:23:57.000
I would also like to draw your attention to the fact

01:23:57.000 --> 01:24:03.000
that the Khator experiments were carried out in 1927-1932,

01:24:03.000 --> 01:24:04.000
in the 20th century.

01:24:04.000 --> 01:24:09.000
In fact, it was the time of the Great Depression.

01:24:10.000 --> 01:24:16.000
First of all, the question was whether the organization would survive,

01:24:16.000 --> 01:24:23.000
and secondly, whether production would be enough to sell certain products

01:24:23.000 --> 01:24:30.000
that would be possible to sell in the conditions of reduced purchasing power of the population.

01:24:30.000 --> 01:24:36.000
So, when we formulated this doctrine of human relations,

01:24:36.000 --> 01:24:40.000
it was based on the fact that

01:24:40.000 --> 01:24:46.000
the whole basis of this school, this direction of management,

01:24:46.000 --> 01:24:50.000
is that a person is a social being.

01:24:50.000 --> 01:24:55.000
Again, let's remember the definition of management that we gave.

01:24:55.000 --> 01:25:00.000
We always talk about social, economic, and social-technical systems.

01:25:00.000 --> 01:25:06.000
In fact, this is a tribute to the school of management,

01:25:06.000 --> 01:25:08.000
to the school of human relations.

01:25:08.000 --> 01:25:11.000
Indeed, a person is a social being,

01:25:11.000 --> 01:25:15.000
that is, he is oriented to the behavior of other people,

01:25:15.000 --> 01:25:18.000
and included in the context of group behavior.

01:25:18.000 --> 01:25:21.000
This is a very important aspect.

01:25:21.000 --> 01:25:25.000
Because if you are in a collective,

01:25:25.000 --> 01:25:29.000
where there is a cool relationship with the leadership,

01:25:29.000 --> 01:25:36.000
then your initiative may have completely different relations and consequences

01:25:36.000 --> 01:25:40.000
in terms of your socialization in this collective.

01:25:40.000 --> 01:25:50.000
If the staff members are in bad relations with their leader,

01:25:50.000 --> 01:25:57.000
and you are trying to build business relations with him,

01:25:57.000 --> 01:26:00.000
then you may be subject to group ostracism,

01:26:00.000 --> 01:26:03.000
that is, you will be isolated within your group,

01:26:03.000 --> 01:26:09.000
and naturally, when you are in isolation,

01:26:09.000 --> 01:26:12.000
it will be hard for you to work.

01:26:12.000 --> 01:26:20.000
And instead of working, you will be immersed in small conflicts,

01:26:20.000 --> 01:26:23.000
that is, you will do anything but work.

01:26:23.000 --> 01:26:25.000
This is what we pay attention to.

01:26:25.000 --> 01:26:27.000
And this is what we pay attention to.

01:26:27.000 --> 01:26:29.000
Again, the fact is obvious.

01:26:29.000 --> 01:26:32.000
Taylor pointed it out, and Fayol talked about it.

01:26:32.000 --> 01:26:35.000
But it is we who put these facts, these events,

01:26:35.000 --> 01:26:39.000
in the basic position of our concept, the concept of management,

01:26:39.000 --> 01:26:43.000
and focus and pay attention to this very fact.

01:26:43.000 --> 01:26:46.000
At the same time, in the doctrine of human relations,

01:26:46.000 --> 01:26:49.000
great attention is paid to the fact that

01:26:49.000 --> 01:26:54.000
we should associate human psychological features

01:26:54.000 --> 01:26:58.000
with the management aspects that arise.

01:26:58.000 --> 01:27:04.000
But it is emphasized that human nature is incompatible

01:27:04.000 --> 01:27:10.000
with the strict hierarchy, with the bureaucracy that exists in any organization.

01:27:10.000 --> 01:27:13.000
This is the 1930s, the 20th century,

01:27:13.000 --> 01:27:20.000
the period of established capitalist production

01:27:20.000 --> 01:27:27.000
with all its tendencies that exist now.

01:27:27.000 --> 01:27:32.000
So, what concerns these tendencies is the hierarchy.

01:27:32.000 --> 01:27:36.000
There is a boss, there are subordinates, there are deputies,

01:27:36.000 --> 01:27:40.000
there are interns, there are assistants, there are secretaries,

01:27:40.000 --> 01:27:46.000
there are referents, there is a certain procedure for passing documents

01:27:46.000 --> 01:27:49.000
in order to get the necessary signature.

01:27:49.000 --> 01:27:53.000
You must get different visas, legal, financial, accounting,

01:27:53.000 --> 01:27:56.000
economic, industrial and economic.

01:27:56.000 --> 01:27:59.000
And only after you have received all the visas

01:27:59.000 --> 01:28:02.000
can you submit a paper for the signature of the boss.

01:28:02.000 --> 01:28:06.000
Getting a visa is a long-term process.

01:28:06.000 --> 01:28:11.000
It happens that the paper gets to the boss only in a week or two,

01:28:11.000 --> 01:28:15.000
or it won't get there at all because someone will wrap the paper somewhere.

01:28:15.000 --> 01:28:18.000
Very often lawyers like to do this.

01:28:18.000 --> 01:28:23.000
And, accordingly, while you are making changes,

01:28:23.000 --> 01:28:25.000
the time will pass.

01:28:25.000 --> 01:28:29.000
I think that the situation today has not changed at all

01:28:29.000 --> 01:28:33.000
since the middle of the last century,

01:28:33.000 --> 01:28:36.000
because large corporations are especially active in this.

01:28:36.000 --> 01:28:38.000
If the corporation is medium or small,

01:28:38.000 --> 01:28:42.000
then the boss is in the zone of direct visibility, direct contact,

01:28:42.000 --> 01:28:44.000
and here we can get the result quickly.

01:28:44.000 --> 01:28:46.000
Although the consequences can be different.

01:28:46.000 --> 01:28:52.000
But if there is a company with already established internal regulations,

01:28:52.000 --> 01:28:54.000
internal regulations,

01:28:54.000 --> 01:28:59.000
then getting a basic signature there is a long-term procedure.

01:29:00.000 --> 01:29:05.000
In the 1930s, we noticed that this bureaucracy

01:29:05.000 --> 01:29:12.000
is incompatible with human desires, with human nature.

01:29:12.000 --> 01:29:16.000
And in this case we are talking about the results

01:29:16.000 --> 01:29:19.000
that can be attributed to management.

01:29:19.000 --> 01:29:24.000
Because this bureaucracy, when we talk about management,

01:29:24.000 --> 01:29:26.000
is manifested primarily.

01:29:27.000 --> 01:29:30.000
There are some written and unwritten management norms.

01:29:30.000 --> 01:29:32.000
You can't jump over your head,

01:29:32.000 --> 01:29:36.000
you can't bypass your boss, and so on.

01:29:36.000 --> 01:29:38.000
And all this must be taken into account

01:29:38.000 --> 01:29:43.000
if you really want a conflict-free existence

01:29:43.000 --> 01:29:46.000
and a resulting existence, both for yourself and for the company.

01:29:47.000 --> 01:29:52.000
The next thing that we pay attention to in the Doctrine of Human Relations

01:29:52.000 --> 01:29:59.000
is that the managers of enterprises, managers of different branches,

01:29:59.000 --> 01:30:02.000
should be guided to a significant degree

01:30:02.000 --> 01:30:05.000
to meet the needs of people.

01:30:05.000 --> 01:30:11.000
Because if you are guided only to technical factors,

01:30:11.000 --> 01:30:15.000
improving machines, their modernization,

01:30:15.000 --> 01:30:20.000
acquiring new capacities, it's all good.

01:30:20.000 --> 01:30:25.000
But these capacities are a set of hardware, a set of machinery.

01:30:25.000 --> 01:30:30.000
Only when someone who can work on this hardware is suitable.

01:30:30.000 --> 01:30:31.000
Only then.

01:30:31.000 --> 01:30:35.000
He produces something on it, and only then it is returned.

01:30:35.000 --> 01:30:40.000
You can buy the most wonderful modern computer

01:30:40.000 --> 01:30:44.000
with a huge number of capabilities,

01:30:44.000 --> 01:30:47.000
a huge hard disk,

01:30:47.000 --> 01:30:49.000
a huge RAM,

01:30:49.000 --> 01:30:52.000
and sit and play Tetris on it.

01:30:52.000 --> 01:30:57.000
It happens very often, by the way,

01:30:57.000 --> 01:31:00.000
when the needs of the hardware

01:31:00.000 --> 01:31:06.000
are much greater than the tasks that are set by the people working on it.

01:31:06.000 --> 01:31:09.000
Then the question arises,

01:31:09.000 --> 01:31:13.000
why invest additional funds

01:31:13.000 --> 01:31:18.000
and acquire those technical capabilities

01:31:18.000 --> 01:31:23.000
that are redundant for solving business tasks,

01:31:23.000 --> 01:31:27.000
for solving those management tasks that arise before me.

01:31:27.000 --> 01:31:30.000
We paid attention to this.

01:31:30.000 --> 01:31:36.000
In fact, if we buy a particular hardware,

01:31:36.000 --> 01:31:38.000
we should take care of it,

01:31:38.000 --> 01:31:42.000
to interest people to work on this hardware,

01:31:42.000 --> 01:31:45.000
and not to spend time on it.

01:31:45.000 --> 01:31:49.000
If you want to be an effective manager,

01:31:49.000 --> 01:31:51.000
you should keep this in mind.

01:31:51.000 --> 01:31:58.000
Secondly, you should organize training of staff to work on this hardware.

01:31:58.000 --> 01:32:00.000
And again,

01:32:00.000 --> 01:32:04.000
you should start from the fact that a person has different needs.

01:32:04.000 --> 01:32:08.000
When a new hardware is bought, I can be afraid that I won't be able to work on it,

01:32:08.000 --> 01:32:11.000
and I will be fired, and someone else will replace me.

01:32:11.000 --> 01:32:17.000
This is a great need to keep a job,

01:32:17.000 --> 01:32:21.000
and this is a need that I want to work here.

01:32:21.000 --> 01:32:23.000
This is a need that can be developed.

01:32:23.000 --> 01:32:26.000
This is a need that can be emphasized.

01:32:26.000 --> 01:32:29.000
And when you buy a particular hardware,

01:32:29.000 --> 01:32:35.000
you should take care that a person does not have fear of work,

01:32:35.000 --> 01:32:38.000
of this most perfect hardware at the moment,

01:32:38.000 --> 01:32:41.000
but that he has a desire to work on it,

01:32:41.000 --> 01:32:44.000
and, accordingly,

01:32:44.000 --> 01:32:52.000
to contribute to the fact that the efforts put in by a person were noticed,

01:32:52.000 --> 01:32:55.000
were rewarded, were set as an example.

01:32:55.000 --> 01:33:00.000
These are the 30s of the 20th century, when we are talking about it.

01:33:00.000 --> 01:33:06.000
And, of course, in the future, this has been used very, very many times.

01:33:06.000 --> 01:33:11.000
This problem has become especially popular today.

01:33:11.000 --> 01:33:15.000
And when we talk about the current trends in management,

01:33:15.000 --> 01:33:17.000
we will pay attention to this.

01:33:17.000 --> 01:33:24.000
Another thing that can be said about human relations,

01:33:24.000 --> 01:33:29.000
is that we are dependent on management.

01:33:29.000 --> 01:33:33.000
In this case, we are talking about what?

01:33:33.000 --> 01:33:41.000
In fact, again, the same theory, the idea of justice, which Foyol introduces.

01:33:41.000 --> 01:33:46.000
But in this case, we emphasize that the productivity of labor,

01:33:46.000 --> 01:33:52.000
and it is very important to keep in mind the manager who organizes the corresponding process,

01:33:52.000 --> 01:33:59.000
will be more effective if the individual reward is supported by the group.

01:33:59.000 --> 01:34:04.000
For example, there is a certain project group,

01:34:04.000 --> 01:34:07.000
which is aimed at achieving a certain result.

01:34:07.000 --> 01:34:12.000
People make different contributions to achieving this result,

01:34:12.000 --> 01:34:14.000
and the result will be achieved.

01:34:14.000 --> 01:34:18.000
Naturally, someone contributed more, someone less.

01:34:18.000 --> 01:34:22.000
This achievement must be evaluated.

01:34:22.000 --> 01:34:27.000
But then you can organize competitions between different groups,

01:34:27.000 --> 01:34:35.000
and the group that achieved the best results can get an additional reward.

01:34:35.000 --> 01:34:37.000
How will they distribute it?

01:34:37.000 --> 01:34:39.000
This is the job of the group leader.

01:34:39.000 --> 01:34:46.000
But in this case, my individual reward is equal to the group's reward.

01:34:46.000 --> 01:34:52.000
And I understand that, yes, I have a significant contribution to solving the problem.

01:34:52.000 --> 01:34:58.000
But if there were no support from my colleagues,

01:34:58.000 --> 01:35:03.000
if there were no contribution from them, I would not have achieved the result.

01:35:03.000 --> 01:35:06.000
This is the informal organization of labor,

01:35:06.000 --> 01:35:12.000
which is the doctrine of human relations that exists.

01:35:12.000 --> 01:35:15.000
It is important for us to contribute to each person,

01:35:15.000 --> 01:35:19.000
but a person is a social being, and we work together with other people.

01:35:19.000 --> 01:35:25.000
So we need to take this social reward into account.

01:35:25.000 --> 01:35:30.000
This is a confirmation of group activity and group significance.

01:35:30.000 --> 01:35:35.000
I, as a member of a successful group,

01:35:35.000 --> 01:35:38.000
this is, again, the task of motivation,

01:35:38.000 --> 01:35:45.000
which is widely spread today in different concepts of motivation,

01:35:45.000 --> 01:35:54.000
in the theory of MacLeland, in the theory of Herzberg, in the theory of oil and others.

01:35:54.000 --> 01:36:00.000
But it was me who practically justified this result

01:36:00.000 --> 01:36:03.000
and got experimental data,

01:36:03.000 --> 01:36:08.000
on the basis of which all these theories of motivation were subsequently developed.

01:36:08.000 --> 01:36:16.000
So, this is what concerns the school of human relations

01:36:16.000 --> 01:36:21.000
or the doctrine of human relations,

01:36:21.000 --> 01:36:31.000
which today is an integral attribute of any concept of management.

01:36:31.000 --> 01:36:39.000
So, we have gradually reached the middle of the 20th century,

01:36:39.000 --> 01:36:47.000
if we look at our original slide on the evolution of governance thought in the 20th century.

01:36:47.000 --> 01:36:59.000
And now we will stop and consider the approaches in management that exist.

01:36:59.000 --> 01:37:05.000
This is a quantitative approach, a systematic approach, a situational approach and an organizational approach,

01:37:05.000 --> 01:37:15.000
which is currently the most fashionable, although perhaps the most indisputable.

01:37:15.000 --> 01:37:20.000
But we will consider this when we come to this organizational approach.
